article.headline: Kidd, Martin post double-doubles in win
article.linkText: Nets run Hornets out of New Orleans
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The New Jersey Nets needed only one good half to run away with their fifth straight victory and keep their new coach's record unblemished. Jason Kidd had 14 points and 12 assists, leading a fast-break offense that went from nonexistent in the first half to unstoppable in the second as the Nets defeated the New Orleans Hornets 91-70 on Monday night. "We finally got the gumbo off our ribs, then we started running," Kidd said. "Once the greyhounds get out and start running like that, it's fun." Kerry Kittles scored 12 of his 16 points in the third quarter as the Nets blew the game open. Kenyon Martin had 13 points on six dunks and grabbed 12 rebounds as New Jersey sent New Orleans to its third loss in a row. Richard Jefferson added 15 points for New Jersey, which has yet to lose since Lawrence Frank took over as head coach four games ago. "We have a veteran group that understands that it's a 48-minute game," Frank said. "Jason Kidd took it to another level as MVPs do." Jamaal Magloire had 22 points and 13 rebounds to lead New Orleans, but was held to seven points in the second half. Darrell Armstrong added 16 points, hitting four 3-pointers, and Jamal Mashburn had 14 points, but New Orleans got little other offensive help in shooting 36 percent from the floor with 23 turnovers. "We're not shooting the ball well as a team," Armstrong said. "It's going to happen sometimes and what you have to do is keep digging ... and hopefully, you can work your way out of it. Hornets coach Tim Floyd said his team player hard. "We just didn't play efficiently; there was a lot of activity with no accomplishment," Floyd said. After shooting about 35 percent with no fast-break points and no free throws in the first half, the Nets started the third period running hard. "When Coach comes and tells us we don't have any free throws, we know we're not going to get any fast-break points settling for jump shots," Kidd said. "Once he told us that, we knew what we needed to do." New Jersey scored 14 points off the break in the third period (18 for the game) and had more points in the quarter (35) than the first half (31). They also got five points at the free throw line. New Orleans, meanwhile, started the quarter 3-for-15 from the floor while committing four turnovers. Kittles' 3 capped a 13-0 run that gave New Jersey a 54-46 lead. Armstrong snapped the Hornets' drought with a 3-pointer, but that failed to disrupt New Jersey's momentum as Kidd found Martin for a jam. "Their athleticism, their quickness in the open floor, their ability to break us down on the dribble ... wore us down in the second half," Floyd said. The Nets hit 10 of their last 12 shots in the third, finishing the quarter on a 25-8 run. Rodney Rogers had 11 of his 13 points in the fourth quarter and his first of two dunks in the period gave New Jersey a 72-57 lead, drawing boos from the crowd. His second dunk was New Jersey's 13th of the game and gave the Nets an 81-67 lead with just under five minutes to go. Rogers later hit a 3 to make it 90-67. New Orleans hit 63 percent of its shots in the first quarter in jumping out to a 24-19 lead. Magloire, held scoreless Saturday by Miami, had 10 points in the period. Magloire later scored on consecutive possessions, sparking an 9-0 run that put New Orleans back in the lead at 35-29 and New Orleans led 37-31 at the half.

Game notes
Hornets G Baron Davis sat out a second consecutive game with a sore left ankle. His condition was listed as day-to-day. ... The Nets, winner of their last four road games, are 13-12 away from home this season, one of three Eastern Conference teams with a winning road record, along with Indiana and Detroit. ... The Nets average 15.4 fast-break points per game. ... Kidd has 26 double-doubles this season.
